  "wordCount": 197,
  "text": "Can you prove it? Really prove it? Mathematical proof? Cambridge 9709. Let's go. Four methods. Every A-level student must know these. First, proof by deduction. Start with what you know. Logical steps to your conclusion. Prove the sum of two even numbers is always even. Let them be 2A and 2B. 2A plus 2B equals two brackets. A plus B. That's even. Proven. Second, proof by exhaustion. Only a few cases. Check them all. Is n squared plus n always even? For n equals 1, 2, 3. 1 plus 1, 2, even. 4 plus 2, 6, even. 9 plus 3, 12, even. All cases done. Third, proof by contradiction. Assume the opposite, then find the contradiction. Proof root 2 is irrational. Assume it equals A over B in lowest terms. Square both sides. 2 equals A squared over B squared. So A squared equals 2B squared. A must be even. But then B must be even too. Both even? Wasn't in lowest terms. Contradiction. Root 2 is irrational. Disproof by counterexample. One example breaks it. All primes are odd. 2 is prime. And even. Disproved. Deduction. Exhaustion. Contradiction. Counterexample. Four methods. Save this. Guaranteed exam marks.",
